The orthodox wisdom has been that the best way to play the great Spaniard is to go more to his backhand, but that has changed in my view and Djokovic, who has beaten him in their past four meetings, has had a lot of success hitting hard to Nadal’s supposedly stronger forehand side.

Over the years, Nadal’s backhand has become an incredibly solid shot, partly because he is a natural right-hander. His defence is phenomenal on that wing.

Another factor is that Rafa’s biggest weapon of all is the ‘inside-out’ forehand he hits when running around his backhand — these are both good reasons not to overdo the hitting towards that side of the court.

Murray has to take the ball on in the way he did in Rome. At times in that match he really hurt Nadal with his backhand and by hitting hard and flat to him on both sides. It was a contest he could have won.

